node.text:
If we protect and restore our oceans from threats like illegal and irresponsible fishing, they can feed ONE BILLION people a healthy seafood meal each day.
.
Wild fish is a healthy source of protein that doesn’t require fresh water or arable land, produces little carbon dioxide, and costs less per pound than beef, chicken, lamb or pork.
.
Sustainable fishery management can help increase the global fish catch by up to 15% from current levels. Oceana campaigns worldwide to win policy victories that protect our oceans and deliver more seafood to the future. #SaveTheOceansFeedTheWorld

node.title: Save the Oceans, Feed the World

We must act together to stop destroying the very planet that sustains us. Join @Oceana, @oak_foundation and the hundreds of organizations that have already signed on to #RiseUp4theOcean.
.
We need to RISE UP together to:
- Restore ocean life
- Invest immediately in a net-zero carbon emissions future
- Speed the transition to a circular and sustainable economy
- Empower and support coastal people
- Unite for stronger global ocean governance
- Protect at least 30% of the ocean by 2030
.
Learn more at RISEUPfortheocean.org
.
#SaveOurOcean #Ocean #SDG14 #OceanClimateAction

node.text: Our oceans are being filled and killed by throwaway plastics. But together, we can create a movement to reduce throwaway plastic at the source and save our oceans. Oceana and our allies are already winning plastic-free victories -- victories that aren't possible without your help. Are you ready to be part of our movement to #BreakFreeFromPlastic? http://bit.ly/32LuWJe

node.text:
Actor, singer, author and producer @jennaushkowitz knows how important sharks are to our oceans. "Sharks are so vital to the ecosystem. They're at the top of the food chain and regulate the first population. And without them, we'd be in real danger."
.
Fins from up to 73 million sharks end up in the global shark fin trade every year. Shark finning is the practice of cutting off a shark's fin, and then often discarding the shark back into the ocean where it drowns. Sharks need your help.
.
That's why we're working with @knockaround to help protect sharks and our oceans. $5 from every pair of @sharkweek Fort Knocks sunglasses will be donated to Oceana. Get your pair from @knockaround and follow the link in our bio to tell Congress to ban the sale of shark fins in the U.S. #FinBanNow
.

node.text: Did you know? Since 1950, more than 18.2 TRILLION pounds of plastic have been produced. And about 100,000 pounds of that plastic ends up in our oceans EVERY THREE MINUTES. And only 9 percent of all plastics produced in the world has been recycled. Our planet is in a plastics crisis and reycling is not the answer. We must start talking about plastics REDUCTION. What can be done? To start, you can pledge to #BreakFreeFromPlastic by visiting OCEANA.ORG/PLASTICS and join us in urging companies to start offering plastic-free alternatives. 🎥: Melissa Forsyth | Oceana #plastics #plastic #pollution #plasticpollution #ocean #oceans #conservation

node.text: DID YOU KNOW collisions with vessels are a top threat to the remaining North Atlantic right whales? Oceana’s new report shows up to 90% of vessels speeding in slow down areas meant to protect these critically endangered whales. If we don’t protect them now, they are going to go extinct. Tell @NOAAFisheries to enforce speeding regulations to protect these whales. Link in Bio. #RightWhaletoSave

Today, 300+ organizations and companies called on @secdebhaaland to have the @nationalparkservice ban single-use plastic in our 423 national parks. Not only would this help curb the plastic pollution threatening our planet's future, but it would also advance @POTUS's goals for addressing environmental justice and the climate crisis. 
.
Learn more about why this move is important and how it benefits both our national parks and the millions of people who visit them each year. Link in bio. 
#PlasticFreeJuly #NationalParks #BreakFreeFromPlastic

URGENT: Sharks need your help. 🦈
.
Fins from up to 73 million sharks end up in the global fin trade every year. The U.S. Senate just passed the Shark Fin Sales Elimination Act (S. 1106). Now a bill to ban the sale of in shark fins in the U.S. (H.R. 2811) has been introduced in the House of Representatives. Tell your representative to protect sharks before it's too late. Link in bio. #FinBanNow
